# LOGO! PG session capture — real hardware
# device: identNo=45 mode=42 passwordExists=1 clearWriteUnlocks=1 blockReadsWork=1 program=010019802180ffffffffffff01001f80
# source: 0BA6.ES10, WebUSB / CH340, fw V1.07.07, 2026-07-17
#
# THE BREAKTHROUGH SESSION. Unlike the 2026-07-16 capture (which used the wrong 0x4740 write and the
# wrong paged addresses), this one:
#   1. recovers the (XOR-obfuscated) password → decodes to "RHOMBUS",
#   2. clears protection with the CORRECT register 0x00FF4800 = 0,
#   3. and reads the program body via READ BLOCK (0x05) at the BARE 0x00003292 — which returns real
#      program data (0BA6 Memory reads are block-only: Read BYTE there returns 0x00).
#
# Format: one exchange per line, "→ <request hex>   ← <response hex | (nothing)>   (note)". The
# replay test (test/session-replay.test.ts) builds a FakeDevice from the `# device:` header and
# asserts the fake produces exactly the recorded response. Per-byte region reads (Read Byte / Read
# Block loops) are logged by the tool only as progress summaries, so they are not individual
# exchanges here — only the single confirming Read Block of the program head is.

# --- connect + confirm STOP + protection flag ---
→ 22   ← 06   (Restart — clears the error state)
→ 21   ← 06 03 21 45   (IdentNo 0x45 = 0BA6.ES10)
→ 55 12 12 aa   ← (nothing)   (STOP to an already-stopped device is not acknowledged)
→ 55 17 17 aa   ← 06 42   (mode = STOP)
→ 02 00 ff 48 ff   ← 06 03 00 ff 48 ff 40   (password IS set: 0x40)

# --- unlock (step 3): restart + re-negotiate, read the flag + magic, then the CLEAR write ---
→ 22   ← 06
→ 21   ← 06 03 21 45
→ 55 17 17 aa   ← 06 42
→ 02 00 ff 48 ff   ← 06 03 00 ff 48 ff 40
→ 02 00 ff 1f 00   ← 06 03 00 ff 1f 00 04   (magic 1 = 0x04)
→ 02 00 ff 1f 01   ← 06 03 00 ff 1f 01 00   (magic 2 = 0x00)
# (password store 0x00000566 ×10 read here as a Read Byte loop → dd c5 df c6 d8 c9 d8 00 00 00,
#  which XOR-decodes through "protect customer" to "RHOMBUS" — summarised, not an exchange)
→ 01 00 ff 48 00 00   ← 06   (CLEAR protection: Write Byte 0x00FF4800 = 0x00 — the register LSC uses)

# --- the confirming Read Block: program head at BARE 0x00003292, 16 bytes → real data + XOR ---
# 01 00 19 80 21 80 ff ff ff ff ff ff 01 00 1f 80 (14/16 non-zero); XOR checksum 0xA7.
→ 05 00 00 32 92 00 10   ← 06 01 00 19 80 21 80 ff ff ff ff ff ff 01 00 1f 80 a7

# --- OBSERVED but NOT yet reproduced by the fake (documented for the record) ---
# • A 512-byte Read Block at the same address is rejected: "→ 05 00 00 32 92 02 00 ← 06 15 03"
#   (illegal access). So the ES10 caps a Read Block telegram well below 512 bytes; 16 works. The
#   tool therefore reads in 16-byte blocks.
# • The block-read window is FRAGILE: after the clear write it stays open across bare Read Bytes,
#   but a mode query (0x55) or a PAGED Read Byte (0x00FF48FF) issued afterwards re-locks it — the
#   next Read Block then returns 06 15 03. (The tool now goes straight from the clear write to the
#   Read Block with no mode/register read in between.)
